sql:
SELECT MAX(research_funding) AS max_research_funding
FROM institution_year_data
WHERE year = 2012;

SELECT total_applications, year
FROM admissions
ORDER BY year ASC;

external_knowledge:
- The term "above-average financial aid" refers to institutions offering average financial aid higher than the overall average across all institutions over the specified 5-year period;
- "Top 10 institutions" are those ranked highest based on their average financial aid over the 5-year period;
- "Access counts" and "download counts" refer to the number of times data from these institutions has been accessed and downloaded, respectively;
- "Average tuition fees" are calculated over the last 5 years for both in-state and out-state students;
- "Average number of days since the year they offered the highest average financial aid" is a measure of how long ago these institutions provided their highest average financial aid, indicating the timeliness of their aid offers.

- "Active educational institutions" refers to institutions that have received applications and enrolled students; 
- "Total financial aid distributed" is the sum of financial aid given to students over the years; 
- "Average financial aid per student" is the average amount of financial aid awarded, calculated by dividing total aid by the number of students who received aid.

sql:
SELECT AVG(npt) AS average_net_price
FROM institution_year_data
WHERE year = 2011;

SELECT graduation_rate
FROM institution_year_data
WHERE unitid = 0 AND year = 2012;

SELECT MAX(graduation_rate) AS max_graduation_rate
FROM graduation_rates
WHERE year = 2011;
